Hydrologists primarily assess **total organic carbon (TOC)** as a key indicator of water quality, reflecting organic pollution and microbial activity that impacts dissolved oxygen levels. While dissolved oxygen itself isn’t listed, TOC is a critical proxy for organic matter influencing oxygen demand. Other options (chlorination, phytoplankton, VOCs) are less directly tied to baseline freshwater health metrics.
